    <div class="about">
      <p>Get a random <a href="https://twitter.com/dril?s=20">@dril</a> tweet</p>
      <p>Since there's no way you've read all 9,891 of them, this is a way of seeing "fresh" posts when you fall down the rabbit hole.</p>
      <p>I cannot believe that something like this doesn't already exist,
         so if you know a better version of this please send me.</p>
      <p>This is not up to date, it takes the links from a static file,
         because I'm too lazy to learn how to deal with twitter APIs. The latest tweet
          is <a target="_blank" href="http://twitter.com/dril/status/1261063616054231041">this one</a>,
           which is from May 14, 2020. I just took the tweets from
           <a target="_blank" href="https://cooltweets.herokuapp.com/dril">this page</a>,
            and put them in a JSON.</p>
      <p>It includes retweets and replys too, so not every tweet was written by @dril</p>
      <p>If you want to do some data analysis on dril tweets, or anything like that,
         you can get all the tweets in here as a JSON file with the text, the date and the link
          for the each tweet. It looks like this:</p>
      <p>{<br>&emsp;"text": "no",<br>&emsp;"link": "http://twitter.com/dril/status/922321981",<br>&emsp;"date": "\nSep 15, 2008 10:25:20 AM\n"<br>}</p>
